718	n341htid3be1yu5mscsoq4nu	System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Education	2026-05-01	\N	Ross	2026-02-02 10:07:13.509	2026-04-20 08:20:53.245	2026-04-20 08:20:53.322	1	3	\N	16:00:00	18:00:00	f	0	\N	Workshop	## Event Overview\n\nJoin us for an interactive workshop exploring best practices for designing and implementing group projects in computer science education. This session brings together educators, researchers, and industry professionals to discuss effective strategies for collaborative learning in technical coursework.\n\n## What You'll Learn\n\n- **Team Formation Strategies**: Evidence-based approaches to creating balanced, diverse teams\n- **Project Scoping**: How to design projects that are challenging yet achievable within academic timeframes\n- **Role Definition**: Establishing clear responsibilities while maintaining flexibility\n- **Version Control Best Practices**: Teaching Git workflows that mirror industry standards\n- **Conflict Resolution**: Handling interpersonal and technical disagreements in student teams\n- **Assessment Design**: Evaluating both individual contributions and team outcomes fairly\n- **Tools & Platforms**: Selecting the right collaboration tools for educational settings\n\n## Why Group Work Matters\n\nModern software development is inherently collaborative. By incorporating well-designed group projects, we prepare students for:\n\n- Agile development environments\n- Code review processes\n- Distributed team collaboration\n- Technical communication skills\n- Project management fundamentals\n\n## Session Format\n\n### Morning Session (9:00 AM - 12:00 PM)\n- **Keynote**: "From Classroom to Codebase: Bridging Academic and Industry Collaboration" \n- **Panel Discussion**: Educators share their successful group project frameworks\n- **Breakout Groups**: Designing a sample group project for your course\n\n### Afternoon Session (1:00 PM - 4:00 PM)\n- **Workshop**: Hands-on activity using GitHub Classroom and project management tools\n- **Case Studies**: Analysis of successful and challenging group projects\n- **Q&A**: Open discussion and problem-solving session\n\n## Featured Speakers\n\n**Dr. Sarah Chen** - Associate Professor, Software Engineering Education  \n_University of Washington_\n\n**Marcus Thompson** - Engineering Manager  \n_GitHub Education Team_\n\n**Prof. Raj Patel** - CS Education Researcher  \n_MIT CSAIL_\n\n## Target Audience\n\n- Computer Science educators (high school through graduate level)\n- Curriculum designers\n- Teaching assistants and instructional staff\n- Educational technology specialists\n- Industry professionals interested in CS education\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\nParticipants will leave with:\n\n- A template for designing group projects in their courses\n- Rubrics for assessing individual and team performance\n- Strategies for managing\n\nLearn more: [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robot](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robot)	Workshop - Saturday 28th Feb, 12am - System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Education	Dear all,\n\nYou are cordially invited to the next Computer Science Education Group Workshop on Saturday 28th February at 16:00-18:00. This event will be online on MS Teams at https://example.com\n\nSpeaker: Ross\n\nTitle: System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Education\n\nAbstract: Explore strategies for structuring collaborative software projects in CS courses. Learn how to form balanced teams, define clear roles, manage code conflicts, and assess individual contributions while fostering teamwork skills essential for industry.\n\nWe hope to see you at the Workshop!\n\nBest regards,\nCSEG Organisers	Workshop - Saturday 28th Feb, 12am - System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Education	Dear all,\n\nThis is a reminder for the next Computer Science Education Group Workshop on Saturday 28th February at 16:00-18:00. This event will be online on MS Teams at https://example.com\n\nSpeaker: Ross\n\nTitle: System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Education\n\nAbstract: Explore strategies for structuring collaborative software projects in CS courses. Learn how to form balanced teams, define clear roles, manage code conflicts, and assess individual contributions while fostering teamwork skills essential for industry.\n\nWe hope to see you at the Workshop!\n\nBest regards,\nCSEG Organisers	Workshop - Saturday 28th Feb, 12am - System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Education	Dear all,\n\nThis is a final reminder for the next Workshop, happening today at 16:00-18:00, online on MS Teams at https://example.com\n\nSpeaker: Ross\n\nTitle: System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Education\n\nAbstract: Explore strategies for structuring collaborative software projects in CS courses. Learn how to form balanced teams, define clear roles, manage code conflicts, and assess individual contributions while fostering teamwork skills essential for industry.\n\nHope to see you there!\n\nBest regards,\nCSEG Organisers	2026-02-21 09:00:00	2026-02-25 09:00:00	2026-02-28 09:00:00	f	f	f	\N	https://example.com	Explore strategies for structuring collaborative software projects in CS courses. Learn how to form balanced teams, define clear roles, manage code conflicts, and assess individual contributions while fostering teamwork skills essential for industry.	t	Online only event	\N	\N	\N	\N	BEGIN:VCALENDAR\r\nVERSION:2.0\r\nPRODID:-//CSEG//CSEG Events Calendar//EN\r\nCALSCALE:GREGORIAN\r\nMETHOD:PUBLISH\r\nBEGIN:VEVENT\r\nUID:System-Design-Project:-Designing-Effective-Group-Work-in-CS-Education20\r\n 26-05-01T00:00:00.000Z16:00:00@cseg.ed.ac.uk\r\nDTSTAMP:20260420T072053Z\r\nDTSTART:20260501T160000Z\r\nDTEND:20260501T180000Z\r\nSUMMARY:System Design Project: Designing Effective Group Work in CS Educati\r\n on\r\nDESCRIPTION:Speaker: Ross\\n\\nAbstract: Explore strategies for structuring c\r\n ollaborative software projects in CS courses. Learn how to form balanced t\r\n eams\\, define clear roles\\, manage code conflicts\\, and assess individual \r\n contributions while fostering teamwork skills essential for industry.\\n\\nL\r\n ocation: Online at https://example.com\r\nLOCATION:Online at https://example.com\r\nEND:VEVENT\r\nEND:VCALENDAR
724	v1jkann5ods4z4nu6gtse8bl	Haskell Automarker	2026-04-30	\N	Bob	2026-04-20 09:15:06.227	2026-04-20 09:15:06.227	\N	3	3	\N	09:00:00	11:00:00	f	0	\N	Workshop	This session explores the design and implementation of an automated marking system\nfor Haskell assignments, integrated directly into MarkEd, the University of Edinburgh's\ninternal marking platform. Starting from the practical challenges of marking functional\nprogramming submissions at scale, we will investigate how automarking can reduce\nmarker workload, improve consistency, and provide faster feedback to students 螕脟枚 without\nsacrificing the nuance that manual marking offers.\n\n## Background\n\nMarking Haskell assignments presents challenges that differ from marking imperative\nlanguages. Functional programs can be correct in their output yet stylistically poor,\noverly complex, or reliant on partial solutions that happen to pass naive test suites.\nAt the same time, the volume of submissions in large undergraduate courses makes\ndetailed manual marking difficult to sustain without significant marker time and\ncoordination overhead.\n\nMarkEd already supports structured feedback and rubric-based marking. This session\nexamines how automarking fits into that existing workflow rather than replacing it.\n\n## What the Session Covers\n\n- The specific marking pain points in Haskell courses at Edinburgh and how they\n  motivated the automarker's design\n- How the automarker integrates with MarkEd's existing rubric and feedback system\n- The technical approach: test suite design, sandboxed execution, and handling of\n  partial and malformed submissions\n- Where automarking works well and where human judgement remains essential\n- Lessons learned from deploying the system in a live course context\n\n## Key Questions We Will Discuss\n\n- How should automarker output be presented to markers and students 螕脟枚 as a score,\n  as structured feedback, or as a flag for human review?\n- What kinds of Haskell errors and edge cases are hardest to handle automatically,\n  and how can rubric design mitigate this?\n- How do students respond to automated feedback, and does it change how they approach\n  resubmission or revision?\n- What are the risks of over-relying on test-suite-based marking for a language where\n  correctness and quality can come apart?\n\n## Who Should Attend\n\nThis session will be useful to anyone involved in:\n\n- Teaching or coordinating functional programming courses\n- Designing or maintaining marking infrastructure\n- Thinking about the role of automated tools in assessment more broadly\n\nNo prior experience with MarkEd or Haskell automarking is assumed. Participants are\ninvited to bring examples from their own courses where automated or semi-automated\nmarking has been considered, attempted, or abandoned, as these will enrich the\nroundtable discussion.\n\n## Format\n\nAfter a short presentation introducing the automarker and its integration with MarkEd,\nthe session moves into a structured discussion. Participants will work through a small\nset of scenarios 螕脟枚 drawn from real marking situations 螕脟枚 to examine where automation\nadds value, where it introduces risk, and how the two can be balanced in a coherent\nassessment workflow.	Workshop - Thursday 30th Apr, 1am - Haskell Automarker	Dear all,\n\nYou are cordially invited to the next Computer Science Education Group Workshop on Thursday 30th April at 09:00-11:00. This event will be online on MS Teams at https://example.com\n\nSpeaker: Bob\n\nTitle: Haskell Automarker\n\nAbstract: Here is an abstract\n\nWe hope to see you at the Workshop!\n\nBest regards,\nCSEG Organisers	Workshop - Thursday 30th Apr, 1am - Haskell Automarker	Dear all,\n\nThis is a reminder for the next Computer Science Education Group Workshop on Thursday 30th April at 09:00-11:00. This event will be online on MS Teams at https://example.com\n\nSpeaker: Bob\n\nTitle: Haskell Automarker\n\nAbstract: Here is an abstract\n\nWe hope to see you at the Workshop!\n\nBest regards,\nCSEG Organisers	Workshop - Thursday 30th Apr, 1am - Haskell Automarker	Dear all,\n\nThis is a final reminder for the next Workshop, happening today at 09:00-11:00, online on MS Teams at https://example.com\n\nSpeaker: Bob\n\nTitle: Haskell Automarker\n\nAbstract: Here is an abstract\n\nHope to see you there!\n\nBest regards,\nCSEG Organisers	2026-04-23 09:00:00	2026-04-27 09:00:00	2026-04-30 09:00:00	f	f	f	\N	https://example.com	Here is an abstract	t	Online only event	\N	\N	\N	\N	BEGIN:VCALENDAR\r\nVERSION:2.0\r\nPRODID:-//CSEG//CSEG Events Calendar//EN\r\nCALSCALE:GREGORIAN\r\nMETHOD:PUBLISH\r\nBEGIN:VEVENT\r\nUID:Haskell-Automarker2026-04-30T00:00:00.000Z09:00:00.000@cseg.ed.ac.uk\r\nDTSTAMP:20260420T081506Z\r\nDTSTART:20260430T090000Z\r\nDTEND:20260430T110000Z\r\nSUMMARY:Haskell Automarker\r\nDESCRIPTION:Speaker: Bob\\n\\nAbstract: Here is an abstract\\n\\nLocation: Onli\r\n ne at https://example.com\r\nLOCATION:Online at https://example.com\r\nEND:VEVENT\r\nEND:VCALENDAR
