36	rp1jw2end93j8zyyjd2dl648	GenAI as a Co-Pilot, Not a Ghostwriter	Dr. Elena Vance	Dr. Mark Thorne, Sarah Jenkins (PhD Candidate)	2023-02-08	f	2026-02-05	2026-02-01 22:58:57.418	2026-02-01 22:58:57.418	\N	1	1	\N	mark@gmail.com, sarah@gmail.com	elena@gmail.com	As Large Language Models (LLMs) become ubiquitous, this project investigates how middle school students can use AI as a "collaborative peer" rather than a shortcut. We are developing a scaffolding interface that forces students to explain the logic of AI-generated code snippets before they can be executed. By tracking "explanation accuracy" against "code performance," we aim to determine if AI-assisted learning accelerates computational thinking or creates a "syntax-crutch" dependency. The goal is a set of pedagogical guidelines for K-12 teachers to integrate AI without sacrificing foundational logic skills.	# GenAI as a Co-Pilot, Not a Ghostwriter\n\n## Project Overview\nThis research addresses the "black box" problem of Large Language Models (LLMs) in introductory programming. When students use AI to generate code, they often bypass the mental models necessary for debugging and architectural design. Our project, **Co-Pilot-Check**, introduces a "Reflective Interstitial" layer in the IDE.\n\n### Summary\n\nAs Large Language Models (LLMs) become ubiquitous, this project investigates how middle school students can use AI as a "collaborative peer" rather than a shortcut. We are developing a scaffolding interface that forces students to explain the logic of AI-generated code snippets before they can be executed. By tracking "explanation accuracy" against "code performance," we aim to determine if AI-assisted learning accelerates computational thinking or creates a "syntax-crutch" dependency. The goal is a set of pedagogical guidelines for K-12 teachers to integrate AI without sacrificing foundational logic skills.\n\n### Research Methodology\n* **Phase 1: The Explainer Interface:** Development of a VS Code extension that intercepts LLM output and requires the user to annotate the code with natural language "logic tags."\n* **Phase 2: Comparative Study:** A randomized controlled trial (RCT) with 200 CS1 students. Group A uses standard GitHub Copilot; Group B uses our "Co-Pilot-Check" interface.\n* **Phase 3: Longitudinal Analysis:** Measuring retention of concepts six months after the initial course completion.\n\n### Key Objectives\n1. **Quantify the "Syntax Crutch":** Measuring if students can reproduce logic without AI after using it.\n2. **Pedagogical Framework:** Creating a "Prompt Engineering for Education" rubric for K-12 instructors.\n\n---\n**Primary Investigator:** Dr. Elena Vance  \n**Co-Investigators:** Dr. Mark Thorne, Sarah Jenkins (PhD Candidate)  \n**Status:** Active - Data Collection Phase	\N
37	rp1jw2end93j8zyyjd2dl648	GenAI as a Co-Pilot, Not a Ghostwriter	Dr. Elena Vance	Dr. Mark Thorne, Sarah Jenkins (PhD Candidate)	2023-02-08	f	2026-02-05	2026-02-01 22:58:57.418	2026-02-01 22:58:57.418	2026-02-01 22:58:57.474	1	1	\N	mark@gmail.com, sarah@gmail.com	elena@gmail.com	As Large Language Models (LLMs) become ubiquitous, this project investigates how middle school students can use AI as a "collaborative peer" rather than a shortcut. We are developing a scaffolding interface that forces students to explain the logic of AI-generated code snippets before they can be executed. By tracking "explanation accuracy" against "code performance," we aim to determine if AI-assisted learning accelerates computational thinking or creates a "syntax-crutch" dependency. The goal is a set of pedagogical guidelines for K-12 teachers to integrate AI without sacrificing foundational logic skills.	# GenAI as a Co-Pilot, Not a Ghostwriter\n\n## Project Overview\nThis research addresses the "black box" problem of Large Language Models (LLMs) in introductory programming. When students use AI to generate code, they often bypass the mental models necessary for debugging and architectural design. Our project, **Co-Pilot-Check**, introduces a "Reflective Interstitial" layer in the IDE.\n\n### Summary\n\nAs Large Language Models (LLMs) become ubiquitous, this project investigates how middle school students can use AI as a "collaborative peer" rather than a shortcut. We are developing a scaffolding interface that forces students to explain the logic of AI-generated code snippets before they can be executed. By tracking "explanation accuracy" against "code performance," we aim to determine if AI-assisted learning accelerates computational thinking or creates a "syntax-crutch" dependency. The goal is a set of pedagogical guidelines for K-12 teachers to integrate AI without sacrificing foundational logic skills.\n\n### Research Methodology\n* **Phase 1: The Explainer Interface:** Development of a VS Code extension that intercepts LLM output and requires the user to annotate the code with natural language "logic tags."\n* **Phase 2: Comparative Study:** A randomized controlled trial (RCT) with 200 CS1 students. Group A uses standard GitHub Copilot; Group B uses our "Co-Pilot-Check" interface.\n* **Phase 3: Longitudinal Analysis:** Measuring retention of concepts six months after the initial course completion.\n\n### Key Objectives\n1. **Quantify the "Syntax Crutch":** Measuring if students can reproduce logic without AI after using it.\n2. **Pedagogical Framework:** Creating a "Prompt Engineering for Education" rubric for K-12 instructors.\n\n---\n**Primary Investigator:** Dr. Elena Vance  \n**Co-Investigators:** Dr. Mark Thorne, Sarah Jenkins (PhD Candidate)  \n**Status:** Active - Data Collection Phase	\N
42	o8m3hducoc10i1l0g2v18flx	Culturally Responsive Algorithm Design	Dr. Maya Little-Cloud	Dr. James Peterson, Anita Desai	2024-01-04	f	2026-02-06	2026-02-01 23:02:25.679	2026-02-01 23:08:57.883	\N	1	1	\N	james@gmail.com, anita@gmail.com	maya@gmail.com	Traditional CS education often feels "identity-neutral," which can alienate students from diverse cultural backgrounds. EthosCode flips the script by centering the curriculum on community-driven data and social challenges.	# EthosCode: Culturally Responsive Algorithm Design\n\n## Project Overview\nTraditional CS education often feels "identity-neutral," which can alienate students from diverse cultural backgrounds. EthosCode flips the script by centering the curriculum on community-driven data and social challenges.\n\n### Summary\n\nStandard CS curricula often rely on abstract or Western-centric examples (e.g., sorting a list of names or bank balances). EthosCode is a multi-institutional study that redesigns algorithmic challenges around community-specific problems, such as optimizing local food distribution or mapping indigenous language patterns. We are measuring "Identity Persistence"螕脟枚the degree to which students from underrepresented backgrounds see themselves as creators of technology rather than just consumers. This project seeks to redefine "rigor" by adding "relevance."\n\n### Core Curriculum Modules\n| Module | Traditional Example | EthosCode Alternative |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Graph Theory** | Traveling Salesman (Sales) | Mobile Health Clinic Routing in Rural Areas |\n| **Big Data** | Ad Click Prediction | Tracking Linguistic Shift in Indigenous Dialects |\n| **OOP** | Employee Payroll System | Intergenerational Knowledge Transfer App |\n\n### Impact Metrics\nWe are utilizing the **Computer Science Attitude Survey (CSAS)** to measure shifts in student confidence and sense of belonging across four different urban and rural school districts.\n\n---\n**Primary Investigator:** Dr. Maya Little-Cloud  \n**Co-Investigators:** Dr. James Peterson, Anita Desai  \n**Collaborators:** Tribal Tech Council, Urban League of Education	\N
45	o8m3hducoc10i1l0g2v18flx	Culturally Responsive Algorithm Design	Dr. Maya Little-Cloud	Dr. James Peterson, Anita Desai	2024-01-04	f	2026-02-06	2026-02-01 23:02:25.679	2026-02-01 23:08:57.883	2026-02-01 23:08:57.932	1	1	\N	james@gmail.com, anita@gmail.com	maya@gmail.com	Traditional CS education often feels "identity-neutral," which can alienate students from diverse cultural backgrounds. EthosCode flips the script by centering the curriculum on community-driven data and social challenges.	# EthosCode: Culturally Responsive Algorithm Design\n\n## Project Overview\nTraditional CS education often feels "identity-neutral," which can alienate students from diverse cultural backgrounds. EthosCode flips the script by centering the curriculum on community-driven data and social challenges.\n\n### Summary\n\nStandard CS curricula often rely on abstract or Western-centric examples (e.g., sorting a list of names or bank balances). EthosCode is a multi-institutional study that redesigns algorithmic challenges around community-specific problems, such as optimizing local food distribution or mapping indigenous language patterns. We are measuring "Identity Persistence"螕脟枚the degree to which students from underrepresented backgrounds see themselves as creators of technology rather than just consumers. This project seeks to redefine "rigor" by adding "relevance."\n\n### Core Curriculum Modules\n| Module | Traditional Example | EthosCode Alternative |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Graph Theory** | Traveling Salesman (Sales) | Mobile Health Clinic Routing in Rural Areas |\n| **Big Data** | Ad Click Prediction | Tracking Linguistic Shift in Indigenous Dialects |\n| **OOP** | Employee Payroll System | Intergenerational Knowledge Transfer App |\n\n### Impact Metrics\nWe are utilizing the **Computer Science Attitude Survey (CSAS)** to measure shifts in student confidence and sense of belonging across four different urban and rural school districts.\n\n---\n**Primary Investigator:** Dr. Maya Little-Cloud  \n**Co-Investigators:** Dr. James Peterson, Anita Desai  \n**Collaborators:** Tribal Tech Council, Urban League of Education	\N
