38	f868rtqrc9lt3mha2j3g8co1	Immersive Debugging: 3D Memory Visualization	Dr. Aris Thorne	Dr. Li Wei	2023-01-30	t	\N	2026-02-01 23:00:28.969	2026-02-03 10:58:28.737	\N	1	1	\N	li@gmail.com	aris@gmail.com	Pointers and memory allocation remain the "Valley of Despair" for introductory C++ students. This project utilizes Virtual Reality (VR) to allow students to physically step "inside" their code. By representing a Linked List or a Binary Search Tree as a physical 3D structure, students can manually "re-wire" pointers and see the immediate impact on the heap and stack. Our research focuses on whether spatial reasoning in a 3D environment translates to fewer logic errors in 2D IDE environments.	# Immersive Debugging: 3D Memory Visualization (VR-Mem)\n\n## Project Overview\nMemory management is a notoriously abstract concept. **VR-Mem** seeks to turn the invisible "Heap" and "Stack" into a physical landscape that students can navigate and manipulate.\n\n### Summary\n\nPointers and memory allocation remain the "Valley of Despair" for introductory C++ students. This project utilizes Virtual Reality (VR) to allow students to physically step "inside" their code. By representing a Linked List or a Binary Search Tree as a physical 3D structure, students can manually "re-wire" pointers and see the immediate impact on the heap and stack. Our research focuses on whether spatial reasoning in a 3D environment translates to fewer logic errors in 2D IDE environments.\n\n### Technical Implementation\n* **Hardware:** Meta Quest 3 & Valve Index.\n* **Backend:** A custom LLVM-based debugger that exports real-time memory states to Unity.\n* **Interactions:** Users use hand-tracking to "grab" a pointer (represented as a tether) and attach it to a new memory node.\n\n### Research Questions\n* Does spatial manipulation of pointers reduce the occurrence of "Dangling Pointer" errors in written assignments?\n* Can VR assist neurodivergent learners who struggle with abstract symbol manipulation but excel in spatial reasoning?\n\nLearn more: [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B)	\N
48	f868rtqrc9lt3mha2j3g8co1	Immersive Debugging: 3D Memory Visualization	Dr. Aris Thorne	Dr. Li Wei	2023-01-30	t	\N	2026-02-01 23:00:28.969	2026-02-03 10:58:28.737	2026-02-03 10:58:28.785	1	1	\N	li@gmail.com	aris@gmail.com	Pointers and memory allocation remain the "Valley of Despair" for introductory C++ students. This project utilizes Virtual Reality (VR) to allow students to physically step "inside" their code. By representing a Linked List or a Binary Search Tree as a physical 3D structure, students can manually "re-wire" pointers and see the immediate impact on the heap and stack. Our research focuses on whether spatial reasoning in a 3D environment translates to fewer logic errors in 2D IDE environments.	# Immersive Debugging: 3D Memory Visualization (VR-Mem)\n\n## Project Overview\nMemory management is a notoriously abstract concept. **VR-Mem** seeks to turn the invisible "Heap" and "Stack" into a physical landscape that students can navigate and manipulate.\n\n### Summary\n\nPointers and memory allocation remain the "Valley of Despair" for introductory C++ students. This project utilizes Virtual Reality (VR) to allow students to physically step "inside" their code. By representing a Linked List or a Binary Search Tree as a physical 3D structure, students can manually "re-wire" pointers and see the immediate impact on the heap and stack. Our research focuses on whether spatial reasoning in a 3D environment translates to fewer logic errors in 2D IDE environments.\n\n### Technical Implementation\n* **Hardware:** Meta Quest 3 & Valve Index.\n* **Backend:** A custom LLVM-based debugger that exports real-time memory states to Unity.\n* **Interactions:** Users use hand-tracking to "grab" a pointer (represented as a tether) and attach it to a new memory node.\n\n### Research Questions\n* Does spatial manipulation of pointers reduce the occurrence of "Dangling Pointer" errors in written assignments?\n* Can VR assist neurodivergent learners who struggle with abstract symbol manipulation but excel in spatial reasoning?\n\nLearn more: [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B)	\N
60	p48j3n8733pnzmas0t666orm	GitHub Copilot	ethan	\N	2026-04-01	f	2026-04-30	2026-04-20 09:18:11.955	2026-04-20 09:18:11.955	\N	3	3	\N	\N	ethan@gmail.com	This research project investigates how the integration of GitHub Copilot into student\nprogramming workflows affects the development of core software engineering skills over\ntime. As AI-assisted coding tools become widespread in both industry and education,\nunderstanding their long-term impact on skill acquisition, problem-solving ability, and\ncode quality is increasingly important for curriculum design and assessment practice.	This research project investigates how the integration of GitHub Copilot into student\nprogramming workflows affects the development of core software engineering skills over\ntime. As AI-assisted coding tools become widespread in both industry and education,\nunderstanding their long-term impact on skill acquisition, problem-solving ability, and\ncode quality is increasingly important for curriculum design and assessment practice.\n\n## Abstract\n\nGitHub Copilot and similar large language model-based coding assistants have been\nadopted rapidly across the software industry. However, their effects on learners who\nencounter them early in their programming education remain poorly understood. This\nproject examines whether students who rely heavily on Copilot during formative\nprogramming courses show differences in debugging ability, algorithmic thinking, and\nindependent code production compared to those who do not.\n\n## Research Questions\n\n- Does regular use of GitHub Copilot during undergraduate programming courses affect\n  students' ability to write correct code independently?\n- How do students' mental models of code differ between Copilot-assisted and\n  unassisted learners?\n- What assessment strategies are most effective at distinguishing genuine understanding\n  from Copilot-assisted output?\n\n## Methodology\n\nThe project uses a mixed-methods approach across two cohorts of first and second year\nundergraduate students:\n\n- **Quantitative strand:** assignment scores, code complexity metrics, and debugging\n  task performance are compared between Copilot-permitted and Copilot-restricted\n  groups over two semesters\n- **Qualitative strand:** think-aloud sessions and semi-structured interviews capture\n  how students reason about code when writing it with and without assistance\n- **Longitudinal tracking:** a subset of participants are followed into their third year\n  to assess whether any observed differences persist or diminish over time\n\n## Key Findings to Date\n\n- Students in the Copilot-permitted group produced syntactically cleaner code on\n  average but showed measurably lower performance on unseen debugging tasks\n- Interviewed students reported uncertainty about whether they understood code they\n  had accepted from Copilot suggestions, particularly in unfamiliar problem domains\n- Instructors reported increased difficulty distinguishing genuine misconceptions from\n  Copilot-introduced errors in submitted work\n\n## Implications for Teaching\n\nThe findings so far suggest that unrestricted Copilot use in introductory courses may\naccelerate surface-level output while slowing the development of deeper debugging and\nreasoning skills. The project is developing a set of evidence-based recommendations\nfor course organisers on how to structure Copilot access across different stages of\nthe curriculum.\n\n## Publications and Outputs\n\n- Mitchell, S., Okafor, J. & Nair, P. (2025). *Copilot in the Classroom: Early\n  Observations from a Controlled Study.* Presented at ICER 2025.\n- Full findings paper in preparation for submission to ACM Transactions on Computing\n  Education.	\N
