oss two cohorts of first and second year\nundergraduate students:\n\n- **Quantitative strand:** assignment scores, code complexity metrics, and debugging\n  task performance are compared between Copilot-permitted and Copilot-restricted\n  groups over two semesters\n- **Qualitative strand:** think-aloud sessions and semi-structured interviews capture\n  how students reason about code when writing it with and without assistance\n- **Longitudinal tracking:** a subset of participants are followed into their third year\n  to assess whether any observed differences persist or diminish over time\n\n## Key Findings to Date\n\n- Students in the Copilot-permitted group produced syntactically cleaner code on\n  average but showed measurably lower performance on unseen debugging tasks\n- Interviewed students reported uncertainty about whether they understood code they\n  had accepted from Copilot suggestions, particularly in unfamiliar problem domains\n- Instructors reported increased difficulty distinguishing genuine misconceptions from\n  Copilot-introduced errors in submitted work\n\n## Implications for Teaching\n\nThe findings so far suggest that unrestricted Copilot use in introductory courses may\naccelerate surface-level output while slowing the development of deeper debugging and\nreasoning skills. The project is developing a set of evidence-based recommendations\nfor course organisers on how to structure Copilot access across different stages of\nthe curriculum.\n\n## Publications and Outputs\n\n- Mitchell, S., Okafor, J. & Nair, P. (2025). *Copilot in the Classroom: Early\n  Observations from a Controlled Study.* Presented at ICER 2025.\n- Full findings paper in preparation for submission to ACM Transactions on Computing\n  Education.	\N
